<article>

  <h2>Context</h2>

  <p>
    The
    <span class="pali" data-pali="āṇāpānasati" data-en="mindfulness of breathing">āṇāpānasati</span>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">sutta</span> appears in
    the Majjhima <span class="pali" data-pali="nikāya" data-en="collection">Nikāya</span>
    (MN 118), delivered by the Buddha to an assembly at Icchānaṅgala. He begins by
    praising the monks who are present for their dedication to practice, specifically
    naming several approaches they have been developing. He then teaches what he calls
    a "noble dwelling" and a "Tathāgata's dwelling":
    <span class="pali" data-pali="āṇāpānasati" data-en="mindfulness of breathing">āṇāpānasati</span>
    — mindfulness of in-and-out breathing — developed and repeatedly practised.
  </p>

  <p>
    What is remarkable about MN 118 is its structural ambition. What begins as a
    discourse on breath meditation turns out to be, by the end, an account of how
    a single meditation object — the breath — fulfils all four foundations of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span> and
    in doing so, matures all seven factors of awakening. The sutta is a complete
    meditation manual compressed into a single sequence.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Sixteen Steps</h2>

  <p>
    The teaching is organized around sixteen steps of practice, grouped into
    four tetrads of four. Each tetrad corresponds to one of the four foundations
    of mindfulness — body, feeling, mind, and phenomena — as taught in the
    Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta. The breath is the thread running through all sixteen;
    what changes is the scope and depth of attention applied to it.
  </p>

  <p>
    The instructions share the same grammatical form throughout. The practitioner
    trains: "I will breathe in [doing this]; I will breathe out [doing this]."
    The training is active and intentional, not passive observation. The breath is
    not simply watched; it is worked with, and the working-with becomes progressively
    more refined as the sequence develops.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Four Tetrads</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>The first tetrad — <span class="pali" data-pali="kāya" data-en="body">kāya</span></strong><br>
    The first four steps work with the body. The practitioner knows when the breath
    is long, knows when it is short, trains to experience the whole body
    (sabba-kāya) in breathing, and trains to calm the bodily formation
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="kāyasaṅkhāra" data-en="bodily formation">kāyasaṅkhāra</span>).
    The progression moves from gross observation — the length of a single breath —
    to the subtler activity of settling the entire body-breath process into stillness.
    "Calming the bodily formation" is not a passive event; it is the result of the
    attention becoming fine enough to notice, and allow, the breath's own natural
    tendency toward ease.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The second tetrad — <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span></strong><br>
    The second four steps work with feeling-tone. The practitioner trains to
    experience
    <span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture; joy">pīti</span>
    (rapture), then
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sukha" data-en="pleasure; happiness">sukha</span>
    (pleasure or ease), then the mental formations
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="cittasaṅkhāra" data-en="mental formation">cittasaṅkhāra</span>)
    as a category of experience arising in breathing, and finally the calming of those
    mental formations. The sequence tracks the natural arc of deepening concentration:
    pīti, the energetic quality of a mind that has found its object, giving way to
    sukha, the quieter pleasure that follows.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The third tetrad — <span class="pali" data-pali="citta" data-en="mind">citta</span></strong><br>
    The third tetrad works directly with the mind. The practitioner trains to
    experience the mind, to gladden the mind, to collect the mind into
    <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="concentration; unification of mind">samādhi</span>,
    and to liberate the mind. Each step is a different quality of attention turned
    on the knowing faculty itself rather than on its objects. Experiencing the mind
    means noticing the mind's current state — contracted, expansive, distracted,
    collected — directly. Liberating the mind means releasing it from whatever
    is constraining it in that moment: agitation, dullness, subtle clinging to
    the pleasant state of the practice itself.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The fourth tetrad — <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="phenomena; qualities">dhamma</span></strong><br>
    The fourth tetrad shifts from concentration to insight. The practitioner trains
    to contemplate impermanence
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>),
    fading away (<span class="pali" data-pali="virāga" data-en="fading away; dispassion">virāga</span>),
    cessation (<span class="pali" data-pali="nirodha" data-en="cessation">nirodha</span>),
    and relinquishment
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="paṭinissagga" data-en="relinquishment; letting go">paṭinissagga</span>).
    These are not conceptual exercises performed on top of the meditation; they are
    qualities of direct observation that arise when the mind is sufficiently stilled
    to see what is actually present: the arising and passing of each breath, each
    moment of experience, each mental event. The last step — relinquishment — is not
    a technique but a natural result: a mind that sees clearly enough has less and less
    to hold.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Mapping onto Satipaṭṭhāna</h2>

  <p>
    The sutta makes explicit what the four tetrads accomplish. Each tetrad fulfils
    one of the four foundations of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">satipaṭṭhāna</span>:
    the first tetrad fulfils contemplation of the body; the second, contemplation
    of feelings; the third, contemplation of mind; the fourth, contemplation of
    phenomena. The Āṇāpānasati Sutta is, in this sense, a concentrated version
    of the Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta — the same complete structure traversed through
    a single object.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sutta then goes further. The four foundations of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">satipaṭṭhāna</span>,
    developed through this practice, fulfil the seven factors of awakening —
    the <span class="pali" data-pali="bojjhaṅga" data-en="factors of awakening">bojjhaṅgā</span>:
    mindfulness, investigation of phenomena, energy, rapture, tranquillity,
    concentration, and equanimity. And the seven factors of awakening, fully
    developed, fulfil knowledge and liberation.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "Monks, mindfulness of breathing, developed and repeatedly practised,
    fulfils the four foundations of mindfulness. The four foundations of mindfulness,
    developed and repeatedly practised, fulfil the seven factors of awakening.
    The seven factors of awakening, developed and repeatedly practised, fulfil
    knowledge and liberation."
    <cite>— MN 118 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Is Distinctive About This Sutta</h2>

  <p>
    The Āṇāpānasati Sutta is sometimes read as a technical manual, and at one
    level it is — the sixteen steps can function as a map for a sitting meditation
    session, moving from initial settling through to insight. But what distinguishes
    it from a bare technique is its insistence on the structural completeness of the
    practice. The breath is not a preliminary to something else; it is the whole path,
    worked in depth.
  </p>

  <p>
    This matters for how the practice is understood. Practitioners sometimes approach
    breath meditation as concentration training and insight meditation as something
    separate — a different practice, a different object, a different aim. MN 118 does
    not support that separation. The fourth tetrad's movement through anicca, virāga,
    nirodha, and paṭinissagga is not a departure from the breath; it is what the
    breath is seen to be, when seen with sufficient clarity. Concentration and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vipassanā" data-en="insight; clear seeing">vipassanā</span>
    are not two practices — they are two aspects of one practice, and this sutta
    describes how they mature together.
  </p>

</article>
